training_organizations.name: Florida DCF – Child Protective Investigator Training
training_organizations.description: The Florida Department of Children & Families runs a specialized training program for its Child Protective Investigators. New hires undergo an academy that covers Florida’s abuse hotline procedures, investigative techniques, evidence collection, and the state’s safety decision-making methodology, preparing them to handle CPS investigations.

training_organizations.name: Florida Community-Based Care Lead Agencies
training_organizations.description: Florida outsources foster care operations and family reunification to regional nonprofit lead agencies known as Community-Based Care (CBC) organizations:contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}:contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}. Examples include ChildNet (managing foster care in Broward and Palm Beach counties), Citrus Family Care Network (Miami-Dade/Monroe), Kids First of Florida (Clay County), and formerly Eckerd Connects (which served the Tampa Bay area). These NGOs hold state contracts to place children in foster homes, manage cases, and provide services to families, while DCF oversees and monitors performance.

training_organizations.name: Florida Institute for Child Welfare (FSU)
training_organizations.description: A research and training institute housed at Florida State University that works to improve Florida’s child welfare system. Through state funding, it conducts studies on CPS policy and outcomes, develops evidence-based practice recommendations, and provides training and technical assistance to DCF and community agencies to enhance child welfare practice.

policies.TribalFoster: No, Tribes within state do not provide foster care
policies.InvestQual_SW: Yes, recommended or preferred, but not required
policies.ReportAnonymous: General public (not mandated reporters) can remain anonymous
policies.ScreenerQual_SW: Yes, recommended or preferred, but not required
policies.FatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Def_Subtype_Abuse: Physical injury includes shaken baby syndrome
policies.Def_Subtype_Neglect: Neglect includes inadequate clothing, food, shelter, health/medical care, and supervision
policies.DefHarm_OtherSpecify: Makes the child unavailable for an investigation (except when fleeing domestic violence)
policies.NearFatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews can be conducted but are not required
policies.InvestReq_OtherSpecify: Information is gathered on the parent's or caregiver's overall functioning, parenting style and disciplinary and behavior management practices; If during the course of the investigation it is determined that there is a need to remove physical evidence from the home, other than taking a child into protective custody, the investigator shall request local law enforcement to initiate a criminal investigation; For all cases determine whether any person alleged to have maltreated a child is employed in an institutional setting or holds a professional license. In instances which the caregiver is found to be responsible for abuse, neglect, or abandonment, the CPI shall determine whether information obtained provides credible evidence to support that children or vulnerable adults within the caregiver's employment may have been or are at risk of being similarly maltreated, in which case the CPI must contact the Florida Abuse Hotline to initiate an institutional investigation.
policies.ReportInfo_OtherSpecify: Names and contact info for any person who can provide assistance to the child
policies.ScreenInfo_OtherSpecify: Names and contact information for any person who can provide assistance to the child or additional info about the family's circumstances; Whether the incident is chronic/ongoing situation; Any known history of abuse, neglect or abandonment; Current condition of the child; Other children in the environment; Name and occupation of the reporter; Relationship between child and reporter; Contact information for the reporter
policies.DefAge_VaryByTypeSpecify: Person is considered a child only if under 18 and not married and has not been emancipated by court order
policies.InvestQual_TrainingSpecify: Requires Florida Certification as a Child Protective Investigator (CPI); Florida Child Welfare Pre-Service Training Program includes classroom instruction, on-line learning, and field activities; The department's training program at the regional and district levels must include results of qualitative reviews of child protective investigation cases handled within the region or district in order to identify weaknesses as well as examples of effective interventions which occurred at each point in the case
policies.ScreenerQual_TrainingSpecify: Periodic training in encouraging reporters to provide their names when reporting abuse, abandonment, or neglect
policies.InvestReq_MHEvalCases_Specify: When available information indicates a mental health condition is believed to be impacting a family member, the investigator must consult with a mental health professional or a substance abuse or mental health professional when there are concerns of a co-occurring substance abuse problem.
policies.InvestReq_MedEvalCases_Specify: Allegations of: injuries to the head or fractures in a child; bruises on a child 5 years of age and under; sexual abuse; sexually transmitted disease in a prepubescent child; malnutrition/failure to thrive, medical neglect, child fatality, and serious emotional problems
policies.CaseManagerQual_TrainingSpecify: Florida Certification as a Case Manager; Florida Child Welfare Pre-Service Training Program includes classroom instruction, on-line learning, and field activities
policies.ExtendedFosterCare_Age_OtherSpec: Generally up to age 21 (until 21st birthday); Up to age 22 (until 22nd birthday), if young adult has disability
policies.InvestReq_PerpInterviewCase_Spec: If alleged perpetrator is a parent/caregiver
